  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA377-kiḷavi">itu cēṭpaṭukkappaṭ ṭāṟṟāṉākiya talaimakaṉ tōḻi kēṭpat taṉṉuḷḷē colliyatu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">This is what HE, who was unable to bear it when being kept at a distance, said to his own heart so that the confidante would hear.</p>
        </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA377">
<l>            maṭaṉmā vūrntu mālai cūṭik</l>
<l>            kaṇṇakaṉ vaippi ṉāṭu mūru</l>
<l>            moṇṇuta larivai nalampā rāṭṭip</l>
<l>            paṇṇaṉ mēva lāki yarituṟ</l>
<l>            ṟatupiṇi yāka viḷiyalaṅ kollō</l>
<l>            vakaliru vicumpi ṉaravukkuṟaip paṭutta</l>
<l>            pacuṅkatir matiyat takaṉilāp pōla</l>
<l>            vaḷakañ cērnta ciṟunutal</l>
<l>            kaḻaṟum melikku nōyā kiṉṟē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>            Won’t we perish, since that [is] a fetter,</l>
<l rend="indent">            experiencing something difficult, being the wish to prepare for</l>
<l rend="indent2">            mounting the palmyra horse, wearing a garland</l>
<l rend="indent2">            [and] praising the beauty of the young woman with bright forehead</l>
<l rend="indent3">            in every village and land of the region of wide area<note place="foot">Can <term xml:lang="ta">kaṇ akal</term> simply be understood as <term xml:lang="ta">akal kaṇ</term>?</note>?</l>
<l>        The small forehead that has joined the hair,</l>
<l rend="indent2">            like the wide moonlight of the fresh-rayed moon</l>
<l rend="indent2">            that had been curtailed by the snake in the wide dark sky,</l>
<l>        has become weakening pain that is murmuring.<note place="foot">With this reading the desire to correct is obvious: the editio princeps simply corrects the sandhi by deleating the superfluous final m. The subsequent editions are not happy with two peyareccams in a row and correct the first one into an absolutive. My take nowadays would be to follow Narāyaṇacāmi Aiyar and read a verbal root for absolutive.</note></l>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="8+9b">
<l>    It [the fetter] has become a weakening pain that grumbles</l>
<l> 	of the small forehead ...<note place="foot">For reasons of syntax this second version might even be preferable, because it is not usual to have two consecutive <term xml:lang="ta">peyareccam</term> forms in -<term xml:lang="ta">um</term> without a dependant clause.</note></l>
</lg>
        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
